## Kalshi-Specific Considerations
- Kalshi contracts are binary (yes/no) — "position size" means number of contracts × price per contract
- Factor in Kalshi's fee structure when calculating actual PnL
- Contracts have a fixed max payout ($1.00) — size accordingly
- Be aware of market liquidity: large orders may not fill at expected price

## Common Pitfalls to Avoid
- **Martingale instinct**: Never increase size after a loss to "make it back" — this is the fastest way to blow up
- **Ignoring fees**: Kalshi fees reduce effective PnL — always model net-of-fees returns
- **In-memory only state**: If bot crashes, bankroll state must survive — always persist to disk after every trade
- **Skipping circuit breakers**: They feel annoying when you're on a losing streak. That's exactly when they matter most.
- **Fixed dollar sizing**: Always size as % of current bankroll, never fixed dollar — fixed dollar doesn't account for bankroll changes

